<HEADLINE>
<P>
TARK WORRIES WHILE UNLV SINKS PACIFIC BY 40 POINTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LAS VEGAS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
No lead is a safe lead if you're a worrier like Nevada Las Vegas Coach Jerry 
Tarkanian. 
</P>
<P>
After watching University of the Pacific trim his ninth-ranked Running Rebels' 
lead to 18 at halftime Thursday night, Tarkanian reinserted his starters to 
help widen the margin. 
</P>
<P>
UNLV responded with the first 10 points of the half and raced to a 116-76 Big 
West Conference victory. 
</P>
<P>
Reserve Barry Young scored a season-high 20 points to lead five UNLV players in 
double figures. 
</P>
<P>
All 12 Rebel players scored as Tarkanian substituted freely after his team 
opened a 25-point lead halfway through the first half. 
</P>
<P>
"I really wanted to rest the first group tonight, but a lot of times that 
backfires," Tarkanian said. "But I like to reward the second group in a 
situation like that." 
</P>
<P>
UNLV led by as many as 44 in the second half in improving to 18-4 overall, 11-1 
in the Big West. Pacific fell to 12-9, 5-7. 
</P>
<P>
The defeat was the worst suffered by the Tigers in conference play since they 
were beaten by 40 points by UNLV in 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
