<P>
P. M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
YOUNG &amp; RUBICAM ADMITS GUILT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
HARTFORD, Conn. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Young &amp; Rubicam Inc., one of the world's largest advertising agencies, 
pleaded guilty today to making $130,000 in illegal payments in its efforts to 
win the contract for the Jamaican tourism account. 
</P>
<P>
The New York-based company was fined $500,000 for conspiring to violate the 
Foreign Corrupt Practices Act by making payments to a Jamaican businessman, 
Arnold Foote Jr., who in turn made payments to Eric Anthony Abrahams, the 
former minister of tourism in Jamaica, said U.S. Atty. 
</P>
<P>
Stanley A. Twardy. 
</P>
<P>
The government alleged that Young &amp; Rubicam made the payments in order to 
win and retain the lucrative Jamaican tourism account, for which it produced 
the award-winning "Come Back to Jamaica" campaign in the early 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
The government, citing "exculpatory evidence recently turned over to the 
government," dropped charges against two Young &amp; Rubicam executives, 
executive vice president Arthur R. Klein and former account supervisor Thomas 
Spangenberg. 
</P>
<P>
A third Young &amp; Rubicam worker, Steven M. McKenna, faces federal perjury 
charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
