<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
BUSH GIVES EVERT HYMAN AWARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Bush presented the fourth annual Flo Hyman award today to Chris 
Evert, saying the retired tennis star represented the game as well as "your 
country with great sportsmanship and dignity." 
</P>
<P>
"We will all miss you on the professional tennis circuit. 
</P>
<P>
(Tennis rivals) Martina Navratilova and Pam Shriver may not miss you," Bush 
said, drawing laughter from a gathering of standout female athletes. "But we 
will." 
</P>
<P>
The Flo Hyman award for courage and dedication is named for the Olympic 
volleyball star who died in 1986. It is sponsored by the Women's Sports 
Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
Evert, 35, retired from professional tennis last year after winning 18 Grand 
Slam events. 
</P>
<P>
"Chris, you long represented not just the game of tennis but your country with 
great sportsmanship and dignity," Bush said. "You are a role model for our 
nation's young women." 
</P>
</TEXT>
